@page "/idempotency"

<PageTitle>Idempotency</PageTitle>

<h1>Idempotency</h1>

<p>
    Every event the framework publishes carries a framework-stamped
    <code>EventId</code>. Event Handlers run behind a per-handler dedup ring
    keyed by <code>EventId</code>: if the same id arrives twice (the at-least-once
    delivery guarantee permits this), the second invocation is a no-op. The
    ring's size is tuned via <code>EdictOptions.IdempotencyWindowSize</code>
    (set in <code>Sample.Silo/Program.cs</code>) — large enough to absorb the
    reorder window the stream provider can produce.
</p>

<p>
    This page is prose only. There is no button. A consumer cannot mint a
    duplicate <code>EventId</code> from the data plane — the field is stamped
    inside the framework as the event is constructed, before publish. The only
    way to artificially repeat an id would be a chaos seam on the outbox, and
    that would tax every event flowing through the common path. We considered
    the demo value of an interactive duplicate-and-watch-it-be-dropped button
    insufficient to justify the cost, so the demonstration is left to the
    framework's own tests.
</p>

<p>
    The dedup ring is part of <code>EdictIdempotencyBase</code>, which every
    consumer's Event Handler inherits transitively via
    <code>EdictEventHandler</code>. Chaos delivery (always-on under
    <code>Edict.Testing</code>) exercises this path implicitly in every
    multi-step workflow test in the framework test suites.
</p>
